resource X is busy with operation Y
operation Y is running
operation Y completed/failed/timed out/cancelled
release lock when terminal


A domain gets an operation-monitor only when it has async operations whose success cannot be known at request time.

one node, one active mutating operation
Site lock all the nodes therein
If anything fails after acquiring lock but before dispatch, immediately mark operation FAILED/CANCELLED and release lock.
If dispatch succeeds but mark-running fails, operation must still be recoverable by monitor or sweeper.


Rules:

Rule 1: no quueing by default ever.
Rule 2: UI block, backend enforces
Rule 3: every mutating action must acquire lock first (full node lock - no hierarchy in v1)
Rule 4: if resource is blocked, request is rejected
Rule 5: read-only actions remained allowed

Operation lifecycle - properly define:
PENDING   = operation created, lock acquired, dispatch in progress
RUNNING   = command dispatched / accepted
SUCCESS   = domain monitor verified success
FAILED    = domain monitor or controller verified failure
TIMEOUT   = manager lease expired
CANCELLED = admin/system force stopped operation

The operation manager is the only authority for resource locks.
Every mutating domain command must acquire an operation lock before dispatch.
The UI may block actions, but backend lock acquisition is the source of truth.
If lock acquisition fails, return RESOURCE_BUSY and do not queue.
Domain monitors do not own locks; they only report completion/failure evidence.
The operation manager verifies fencing token and releases lock only on terminal state.
Use coarse node-level locks for V1.
Do not allow software update, RF toggle, or service commands while restart/update is active.

One resource, one active mutation, one operation lifecycle, one authority for lock release.

